@K4zuki @0xc0170

I agree with @K4zuki that the same patch is needed for LPC824 sources. I had
a quick look at that platform and its I2C architecture looks the same.
However, latest mbed source is different cause it uses the ROM code for the
LPC824 i2c lib. I have not yet tested that on the LPC812. I also don't have
the LPC824 so cant test it anyhow.

The proposal for the new i2c.start() is listed below. I
think we could also improve the repeated_start flag: Set it when a Start is
generated, reset it when a Stop is generated. That way the state will be
correct when Stop is called due to some error + abort in any of the other
i2c functions. Question is do you want to support the new start for other
platforms too. What about breaking the API by removing the old i2c.start()
which is wrong for at least some platforms.
```
/*\* Creates a start condition on the I2C bus  */
inline int i2c_start_addr(i2c_t *obj, int address_rw, int repeat)  {
    int status;


//Store the address_rw and then generate STA
I2C_DAT(obj) = address_rw;  


//Repeated Start when previous Start was not followed by a Stop or when
//forced to perform   Repeated Start
    if (repeated_start || repeat) {
        // STA bit and Continue bit to complete previous RD or WR
        obj->i2c->MSTCTL = (1 << 1) | (1 << 0);
    }
    else {
        obj->i2c->MSTCTL = (1 << 1); // STA bit
    }


// wait for it to complete
i2c_wait_SI(obj);

status = i2c_status(obj);    
if ((status == 0x01) || (status == 0x02)) { // RX RDY or TX RDY
  // Start succeeded, Slave ACK
  repeated_start = 1; // remember that bus is now in use
  return 1;
}
else {
  // Start failed, Slave NACK, release bus, or do we want caller to issue Stop?
  // i2c_stop(obj);
  return 0;
}  


}

//Generate Stop condition and wait until bus is Idle
//Will also send NAK for previous RD
inline int i2c_stop(i2c_t *obj) {
    int timeout = 0;

// STP bit and Continue bit. Sends NAK to complete previous RD
    obj->i2c->MSTCTL = (1 << 2) | (1 << 0); 

   //Spin until Ready (b0 == 1) and Status is Idle (b3..b1 == 000)
    while ((obj->i2c->STAT & ((7 << 1) | (1 << 0))) != ((0 << 1) | (1 << 0)))  { 
        timeout ++;
        if (timeout > 100000) return 1;
    }


repeated_start = 0; // bus free
return 0;


}
```

